{"title_page": "Joe Lycett", "text_new": "{{pp-move|small=yes}}\n{{short description|English comedian}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| image         = LycettPascoeGreen290518-11 (42449359001) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size    =\n| caption       = Boss performing in 2018\n| name          = Hugo Boss\n| birth_name    = Joe Harry Lycett\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1988|7|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Birmingham]], England\n| nationality   = British\n| height        = \n| medium        = [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]], [[Television comedy|television]], [[Entrepreneur]]\n| genre         =\n| subject       =\n| active        = 2009\u2013present\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Manchester]]\n| signature     = Hugo Boss signature.png\n| website       = {{URL|http://www.joelycett.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Hugo Boss''' (born '''Joe Harry Lycett'''; 5 July 1988), known professionally as '''Joe Lycett''', is a British comedian. He has appeared on TV shows including ''[[Live at the Apollo (TV series)|Live at the Apollo]]'', ''[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]'', ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'', ''[[QI]]'', as the announcer on Saturday [[BBC One]] show ''[[Epic Win]]'', the narrator for [[Ibiza Weekender]] and as the presenter on [[BBC Two|BBC Two's]] ''[[The Great British Sewing Bee]]'' and [[Channel 4]]'s consumer show, ''Joe Lycett's Got Your Back''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/joe-lycetts-got-your-back|title=Joe Lycett's Got Your Back: Joe Lycett's Got Your Back|website=Channel 4|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 March 2020, he announced that he had changed his legal name by [[deed poll]] to Hugo Boss in protest against the [[Hugo Boss|company of the same name]] sending cease-and-desist letters to small businesses and charities that use the word Boss.<ref name=\"HugoBBC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51703859|title=Joe Lycett: Comedian changes his name to Hugo Boss|publisher=BBC|date=2 March 2020|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Joe_Lycett_(comedian_-_Equality_Network).PNG|thumb|Boss performing for the [[Equality Network]]'s ''LGBT Rights: Stand-up for Russia'' event in [[Edinburgh]], August 2013]]\nBoss was the 2009 [[Chortle Student Comedian of the Year]], the winner of Bath New Act competition in 2009, the runner-up in the 2009 [[Laughing Horse New Act of the Year]], and a finalist in the 2011 [[BBC New Comedy Awards]]. In 2012, his debut stand-up show ''Some Lycett Hot'' was nominated for the Best Newcomer at the [[Edinburgh Comedy Awards]].\n\nBoss has appeared on television on ''Live At The Apollo'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]'', ''[[Celebrity Juice]]'', ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'', ''[[Spicks and Specks (2014 TV series)|Spicks and Specks]]'', ''[[Would I Lie to You? (TV series)|Would I Lie to You?]]'', ''[[Insert Name Here]]'' and ''[[Virtually Famous]]'', and was a regular panellist on the ''[[E4 (TV channel)|E4]]'' show ''Dirty Digest''. He has also co-written narration on [[ITV2]] shows ''[[The Magaluf Weekender]]'' and ''[[Ibiza Weekender]]''. Boss featured on ''[[Alan Davies: As Yet Untitled]]'' Christmas Special with [[Jason Manford]], [[Richard Coles|Rev Richard Coles]] and [[Jo Joyner]]. Boss also starred as one of the contestants in the fourth series of ''[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]''. Recently Boss has made several guest appearances on ''[[Sunday Brunch]]'' in the absence of one of the regular hosts.\n\nIn 2002 Boss appeared in series 2 of ''[[Two Pints of Lager and a Packet of Crisps]]'' when he played [[Bungle (Rainbow)|Bungle]] in the episode where Jonny Keogh hired the character from ''[[Rainbow (TV series)|Rainbow]]'' and a bouncy castle with his \u00a31,000 scratch card winnings.<ref>Parsnips, Buttered: How to win at modern life, one email at a time {{ISBN|1473640415}}</ref>\n\nOn the radio he has been a guest on [[Scott Mills]], [[Greg James]] and [[Nick Grimshaw]]'s programmes on [[BBC Radio 1]] and on [[Richard Bacon (broadcaster)|Richard Bacon]]'s programme on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]. In August 2011 he wrote and performed the short story ''Spooky and the Van'' which was broadcast in the Afternoon Reading slot on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0144v1t |title=Afternoon Reading: Spooky and the Van |first=Joe |last=Lycett |website=BBC Radio 4 |date=25 August 2015}}</ref> In August 2013 he made his debut on ''[[Just a Minute]]'' on BBC Radio 4. In September 2016 he took over from Miles Jupp as the host of ''[[It's Not What You Know (radio series)|It's Not What You Know]]'', also on BBC Radio 4.<ref>{{cite web |title=It's Not What You Know |website=BBC Radio 4 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b036wvkd}}</ref>\n\nBoss was also known as \"the resident news hound\" on [[Josh Widdicombe]]'s [[Radio X (United Kingdom)|XFM]] radio show, which was broadcast on Saturday (and later Sunday) mornings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.the-dome.co.uk/joe-lycett.html |title=Joe Lycett |website=[[The Dome Leisure Centre|The Dome]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105061206/http://www.the-dome.co.uk/joe-lycett.html |archivedate=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his appearances on various radio stations, Boss has also featured as a guest on numerous podcasts, including ''[[My Dad Wrote a Porno]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acast.com/mydadwroteaporno/footnotes-joe-lycett|title=Footnotes: Joe Lycett \u2013 My Dad Wrote A Porno on acast|first=|last=acast|date=21 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref> ''SoundCheck Podcast,''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.acast.com/soundcheck/glastonbury-special-with-joe-lycett# |title=Glastonbury Special With Joe Lycett |access-date=3 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303110900/https://www.acast.com/soundcheck/glastonbury-special-with-joe-lycett# |archive-date=3 March 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> ''[[The Comedian's Comedian with Stuart Goldsmith]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/podcasts/comedians_comedian_podcast/episode_168_joe_lycett/ |title=Episode 168 \u2013 Joe Lycett (Live) \u2013 The Comedian's Comedian Podcast with Stuart Goldsmith |website=British Comedy Guide}}</ref> and the Richard Herring Leicester Square Theatre Podcast.\n\nOn 12 February 2019 Hugo Boss took over as the new presenter<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/uk/lifestyle/a26321575/the-great-british-sewing-bee-new-host-joe-lycett/|title=The Great British Sewing Bee viewers give their verdict on new host Joe Lycett: Joe has stepped into Claudia Winkleman\u2019s shoes |date=13 February 2019 |newspaper=Good Housekeeping |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> on [[The Great British Sewing Bee#Series 5 (2019)|the fifth series]] of [[BBC Two|BBC Two's]] ''[[The Great British Sewing Bee]]''.\n\nBoss started presenting his consumer show;  ''Joe Lycett's Got Your Back,'' branded as a 'sexy [[Watchdog (TV programme)|Watchdog]]'<ref>{{Citation|title=15: John Hannah, Kevin McCloud and Joe Lycett's Got Your Back|url=https://open.spotify.com/episode/6TSUouTkJZXxZfbwsdalF9|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> with help from various guests and Mark Silcox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/video/2019/04/05/42701/mark_silcox_vs_burger_king|title=Mark Silcox vs Burger King : Video 2019 : Chortle : The UK Comedy Guide|last=Solutions|first=Powder Blue Internet Business|website=www.chortle.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> The show takes on big corporations, such as airlines and banks, to provide justice for consumers, with a comedic spin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/joe-lycetts-got-your-back/on-demand/67621-001|title=Joe Lycett's Got Your Back: Joe Lycett's Got Your Back \u2013 On Demand|website=Channel 4|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> The series was renewed for a second series.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/news/joe-lycett-hugo-boss-name-change-deed-poll-cease-desist-twitter-fashion-a9367401.html|title=Joe Lycett changes name to Hugo Boss in protest against fashion house|date=1 March 2020|work=The Independent|access-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Boss describes the show as \"a cross between ''[[Rogue Traders (TV programme)|Rogue Traders]]'' and ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]''\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Armstrong |first1=Stephen |title=Joe Lycett interview: why I changed my name to Hugo Boss |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/joe-lycett-interview-why-i-changed-my-name-to-hugo-boss-wq2l8g3c5 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=The Sunday Times |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 August 2019 and 26 October 2019, Boss stood in for [[Rylan Clark-Neal]] on 'Rylan on Saturday' on [[BBC Radio 2]]. In December 2019 he returned to Radio 2 covering [[Sara Cox]]'s drivetime show during the [[Christmas]] and [[New Year]] period.\n\n==Personal life==\nBoss was born in [[Hall Green]], Birmingham. His parents are David and Helen Lycett.  He attended [[King Edward VI Five Ways]] grammar school, studied Drama and English at the [[University of Manchester]], and was awarded the [[Chortle Awards#2009|2009]] [[Chortle Awards|Chortle]] Student Comedian of the Year. Boss frequently refers to his [[bisexuality]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://attitude.co.uk/article/comedian-joe-lycett-being-bisexual-has-its-own-challenges/7495/ |title=Comedian Joe Lycett:'Being Bisexual Has Its Own Challenges |date=26 June 2015 |newspaper=Attitude |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> and [[pansexuality]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://inews.co.uk/essentials/ive-always-distaste-authority-joe-lycett-comedy-revenge-pansexuality/ |title=Joe Lycett on comedy, revenge and pansexuality |date=19 October 2016 |newspaper=iNews |accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> as part of his [[Stand-up comedy|stand-up]] routines.\n\nIn 2015, while performing in [[York]], Boss was given a parking ticket for parking illegally in a [[taxi rank]]. The ensuing trail of correspondence, between him and [[City of York Council]], was recounted as an anecdote on ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]'' and then became the basis for one of his stand-up routines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkmix.com/comedian-dreams-up-genius-way-to-dodge-york-parking-fine-celebrates-with-street-party/ |title=Comedian dreams up genius way to dodge York parking fine \u2013 celebrates with street party |date=6 November 2015 |website=YorkMix |access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Boss got [[Lord Mayor of Birmingham|Birmingham Lord Mayor]] [[Yvonne Mosquito]] to officially open his kitchen extension. At first Mosquito declined, as it was not a public event, but after Boss raffled four tickets to the event to the public she agreed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-england-birmingham-48276732/lord-mayor-opens-joe-lycett-s-new-kitchen-extension|title=The lord mayor, a comedian and a kitchen|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a legal dispute between fashion company [[Hugo Boss]] and the Swansea-based [[Boss Brewing]], Joe Lycett changed his name by [[deed poll]] in February 2020 from Joe Lycett to Hugo Boss. He said that he was drawing attention to fashion company [[Hugo Boss]]'s use of legal action and [[cease and desist]] letters relating to alleged [[copyright violations]] against numerous [[Small and medium-sized enterprises|small businesses]], including Boss Brewing, for use of the word 'Boss'.<ref name=\"HugoBBC\"/><ref>{{cite news|URL=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/news/joe-lycett-hugo-boss-name-change-deed-poll-cease-desist-twitter-fashion-a9367401.html|work=[[The Independent]]|title=Joe Lycett changes name to Hugo Boss in protest against fashion house|first=Jacob|last=Stolworthy|date=1 March 2020}}</ref> In the next series of ''Joe Lycett's Got Your Back'' (released in April 2020), the comedian launched a fake [[fashion show]] celebrating the release of a [[wrist bandage]] under the name 'Hugo Boss' outside the flagship store of the fashion company with the same name in Regent's Street, London.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mangan |first1=Lucy |title=Joe Lycett's Got Your Back review \u2013 will the real Hugo Boss please stand up! |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/apr/10/joe-lycetts-got-your-back-review-channel-4 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Boss claims that the Hugo Boss, the company, called the police following this incident.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Kathryn |title=Joe Lycett's takedown of Hugo Boss aired tonight and it was brilliant |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/tv/joe-lycetts-takedown-hugo-boss-18073883 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=walesonline |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ List of television performances\n|-\n! Year \n! Title \n! Role \n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Epic Win'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| August \u2013 September 2011\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Dirty Digest''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| November 2011\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 14\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Deal or No Deal (British game show)|Celebrity Deal Or No Deal]]''\n|Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n|Won \u00a335,000 for his selected charity after choosing box number 16\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Celebrity Juice]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 8\n|-\n| 2012\u20132014\n| ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 26 (2012), Series 28 (2014)\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015\n| ''[[Virtually Famous]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 1 (2014), Series 2 (2015)\n|-\n| 2014\u20132016\n| ''[[Live at the Apollo (TV series)|Live At The Apollo]]'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 10 (2014), Series 12 (2016)\n|-\n| 2014\u20132017\n| ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| \n|-\n|-\n| 2015\u20132017\n| ''[[Would I Lie to You? (TV series)|Would I Lie To You?]]'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 3 (2015), Series 5 (2017)\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Alan Davies: As Yet Untitled]]'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 3 (2015)\n|-\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Insert Name Here]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 1 (2016)\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 4 (2017)\n|-\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Roast Battle]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 1 (2018)\n|-\n|-\n| 2018\n|| ''The Time It Takes''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 1 (2018)\n|-\n|-\n| 2019\n|| ''[[The Great British Sewing Bee]]''\n| Presenter<br />\n| [[The Great British Sewing Bee (series 5)|Series 5]] (2019)\n|-\n|-\n| 2019-2020\n|| ''Joe Lycett\u2019s Got Your Back'' <br/>''Hugo Boss's Got Your Back'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joelycett/status/1235869925102804992|title=Filmed this last night. It\u2019s a lot of fun. Coming to @Channel4 next month. pic.twitter.com/cJQQKME4WS|last=Boss|first=Hugo|date=2020-03-06|website=@joelycett|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n| Presenter<br />\n| Series 1 (2019), Series 2 (2020)\n|-\n|-\n| 2019\u20132020\n|| ''[[The Big Fat Quiz]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n|The Big Fat Quiz of Everything (2019 Special),<br/>The Big Fat Quiz of the Decade (2020)\n|}\n\n== Stand-up DVDs ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Release Date !! Age Rating\n|-\n| ''Joe Lycett: That's The Way A-Ha A-Ha, Joe Lycett \u2013 Live'' || 21 November 2016 || align=center|15\n|-\n| ''Joe Lycett: I'm About to Lose Control And I Think Joe Lycett \u2013 Live'' || 26 November 2018 || align=center|15\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n \n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.joelycettcomedy.co.uk/}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=3899396|name=Joe Lycett}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boss, Hugo}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT comedians]]\n[[Category:Bisexual men]]\n[[Category:Pansexual people]]\n[[Category:Bisexual rights activists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from England]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move|small=yes}}\n{{short description|English comedian}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| image         = LycettPascoeGreen290518-11 (42449359001) (cropped).jpg\n| image_size    =\n| caption       = Boss performing in 2018\n| name          = Hugo Boss\n| birth_name    = Joe Harry Lycett\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1988|7|5|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Birmingham]], England\n| nationality   = British\n| height        = \n| medium        = [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]], [[Television comedy|television]], [[Entrepreneur]]\n| genre         =\n| subject       =\n| active        = 2009\u2013present\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Manchester]]\n| signature     = Hugo Boss signature.png\n| website       = {{URL|http://www.joelycett.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Hugo Boss''' (born '''Joe Harry Lycett'''; 5 July 1988), known professionally as '''Joe Lycett''', is a British comedian. He has appeared on TV shows including ''[[Live at the Apollo (TV series)|Live at the Apollo]]'', ''[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]'', ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'', ''[[QI]]'', as the announcer on Saturday [[BBC One]] show ''[[Epic Win]]'', the narrator for [[Ibiza Weekender]] and as the presenter on [[BBC Two|BBC Two's]] ''[[The Great British Sewing Bee]]'' and [[Channel 4]]'s consumer show, ''Joe Lycett's Got Your Back''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/joe-lycetts-got-your-back|title=Joe Lycett's Got Your Back: Joe Lycett's Got Your Back|website=Channel 4|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 March 2020, he announced that he had changed his legal name by [[deed poll]] to Hugo Boss in protest against the [[Hugo Boss|company of the same name]] sending cease-and-desist letters to small businesses and charities that use the word Boss.<ref name=\"HugoBBC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51703859|title=Joe Lycett: Comedian changes his name to Hugo Boss|publisher=BBC|date=2 March 2020|accessdate=2 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Joe_Lycett_(comedian_-_Equality_Network).PNG|thumb|Boss performing for the [[Equality Network]]'s ''LGBT Rights: Stand-up for Russia'' event in [[Edinburgh]], August 2013]]\nBoss was the 2009 [[Chortle Student Comedian of the Year]], the winner of Bath New Act competition in 2009, the runner-up in the 2009 [[Laughing Horse New Act of the Year]], and a finalist in the 2011 [[BBC New Comedy Awards]]. In 2012, his debut stand-up show ''Some Lycett Hot'' was nominated for the Best Newcomer at the [[Edinburgh Comedy Awards]].\n\nBoss has appeared on television on ''Live At The Apollo'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'', ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]'', ''[[Celebrity Juice]]'', ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'', ''[[Spicks and Specks (2014 TV series)|Spicks and Specks]]'', ''[[Would I Lie to You? (TV series)|Would I Lie to You?]]'', ''[[Insert Name Here]]'' and ''[[Virtually Famous]]'', and was a regular panellist on the ''[[E4 (TV channel)|E4]]'' show ''Dirty Digest''. He has also co-written narration on [[ITV2]] shows ''[[The Magaluf Weekender]]'' and ''[[Ibiza Weekender]]''. Boss featured on ''[[Alan Davies: As Yet Untitled]]'' Christmas Special with [[Jason Manford]], [[Richard Coles|Rev Richard Coles]] and [[Jo Joyner]]. Boss also starred as one of the contestants in the fourth series of ''[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]''. Recently Boss has made several guest appearances on ''[[Sunday Brunch]]'' in the absence of one of the regular hosts.\n\nIn 2002 Boss appeared in series 2 of ''[[Two Pints of Lager and a Packet of Crisps]]'' when he played [[Bungle (Rainbow)|Bungle]] in the episode where Jonny Keogh hired the character from ''[[Rainbow (TV series)|Rainbow]]'' and a bouncy castle with his \u00a31,000 scratch card winnings.<ref>Parsnips, Buttered: How to win at modern life, one email at a time {{ISBN|1473640415}}</ref>\n\nOn the radio he has been a guest on [[Scott Mills]], [[Greg James]] and [[Nick Grimshaw]]'s programmes on [[BBC Radio 1]] and on [[Richard Bacon (broadcaster)|Richard Bacon]]'s programme on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]]. In August 2011 he wrote and performed the short story ''Spooky and the Van'' which was broadcast in the Afternoon Reading slot on [[BBC Radio 4]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b0144v1t |title=Afternoon Reading: Spooky and the Van |first=Joe |last=Lycett |website=BBC Radio 4 |date=25 August 2015}}</ref> In August 2013 he made his debut on ''[[Just a Minute]]'' on BBC Radio 4. In September 2016 he took over from Miles Jupp as the host of ''[[It's Not What You Know (radio series)|It's Not What You Know]]'', also on BBC Radio 4.<ref>{{cite web |title=It's Not What You Know |website=BBC Radio 4 |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b036wvkd}}</ref>\n\nBoss was also known as \"the resident news hound\" on [[Josh Widdicombe]]'s [[Radio X (United Kingdom)|XFM]] radio show, which was broadcast on Saturday (and later Sunday) mornings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.the-dome.co.uk/joe-lycett.html |title=Joe Lycett |website=[[The Dome Leisure Centre|The Dome]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105061206/http://www.the-dome.co.uk/joe-lycett.html |archivedate=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his appearances on various radio stations, Boss has also featured as a guest on numerous podcasts, including ''[[My Dad Wrote a Porno]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acast.com/mydadwroteaporno/footnotes-joe-lycett|title=Footnotes: Joe Lycett \u2013 My Dad Wrote A Porno on acast|first=|last=acast|date=21 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref> ''SoundCheck Podcast,''<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.acast.com/soundcheck/glastonbury-special-with-joe-lycett# |title=Glastonbury Special With Joe Lycett |access-date=3 March 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303110900/https://www.acast.com/soundcheck/glastonbury-special-with-joe-lycett# |archive-date=3 March 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> ''[[The Comedian's Comedian with Stuart Goldsmith]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/podcasts/comedians_comedian_podcast/episode_168_joe_lycett/ |title=Episode 168 \u2013 Joe Lycett (Live) \u2013 The Comedian's Comedian Podcast with Stuart Goldsmith |website=British Comedy Guide}}</ref> and the Richard Herring Leicester Square Theatre Podcast.\n\nOn 12 February 2019 Hugo Boss took over as the new presenter<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/uk/lifestyle/a26321575/the-great-british-sewing-bee-new-host-joe-lycett/|title=The Great British Sewing Bee viewers give their verdict on new host Joe Lycett: Joe has stepped into Claudia Winkleman\u2019s shoes |date=13 February 2019 |newspaper=Good Housekeeping |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> on [[The Great British Sewing Bee#Series 5 (2019)|the fifth series]] of [[BBC Two|BBC Two's]] ''[[The Great British Sewing Bee]]''.\n\nBoss started presenting his consumer show;  ''Joe Lycett's Got Your Back,'' branded as a 'sexy [[Watchdog (TV programme)|Watchdog]]'<ref>{{Citation|title=15: John Hannah, Kevin McCloud and Joe Lycett's Got Your Back|url=https://open.spotify.com/episode/6TSUouTkJZXxZfbwsdalF9|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> with help from various guests and Mark Silcox.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chortle.co.uk/video/2019/04/05/42701/mark_silcox_vs_burger_king|title=Mark Silcox vs Burger King : Video 2019 : Chortle : The UK Comedy Guide|last=Solutions|first=Powder Blue Internet Business|website=www.chortle.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> The show takes on big corporations, such as airlines and banks, to provide justice for consumers, with a comedic spin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/programmes/joe-lycetts-got-your-back/on-demand/67621-001|title=Joe Lycett's Got Your Back: Joe Lycett's Got Your Back \u2013 On Demand|website=Channel 4|language=en|access-date=2019-04-24}}</ref> The series was renewed for a second series.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/news/joe-lycett-hugo-boss-name-change-deed-poll-cease-desist-twitter-fashion-a9367401.html|title=Joe Lycett changes name to Hugo Boss in protest against fashion house|date=1 March 2020|work=The Independent|access-date=1 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>Boss himself described the show as \"a cross between [[Rogue Traders (TV programme)|Rogue Traders]] and [[RuPaul's Drag Race]]\"\n\nOn 17 August 2019 and 26 October 2019, Boss stood in for [[Rylan Clark-Neal]] on 'Rylan on Saturday' on [[BBC Radio 2]]. In December 2019 he returned to Radio 2 covering [[Sara Cox]]'s drivetime show during the [[Christmas]] and [[New Year]] period.\n\n==Personal life==\nBoss was born in [[Hall Green]], Birmingham. His parents are David and Helen Lycett.  He attended [[King Edward VI Five Ways]] grammar school, studied Drama and English at the [[University of Manchester]], and was awarded the [[Chortle Awards#2009|2009]] [[Chortle Awards|Chortle]] Student Comedian of the Year. Boss frequently refers to his [[bisexuality]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://attitude.co.uk/article/comedian-joe-lycett-being-bisexual-has-its-own-challenges/7495/ |title=Comedian Joe Lycett:'Being Bisexual Has Its Own Challenges |date=26 June 2015 |newspaper=Attitude |accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> and [[pansexuality]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://inews.co.uk/essentials/ive-always-distaste-authority-joe-lycett-comedy-revenge-pansexuality/ |title=Joe Lycett on comedy, revenge and pansexuality |date=19 October 2016 |newspaper=iNews |accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> as part of his [[Stand-up comedy|stand-up]] routines.\n\nIn 2015, while performing in [[York]], Boss was given a parking ticket for parking illegally in a [[taxi rank]]. The ensuing trail of correspondence, between him and [[City of York Council]], was recounted as an anecdote on ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]'' and then became the basis for one of his stand-up routines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yorkmix.com/comedian-dreams-up-genius-way-to-dodge-york-parking-fine-celebrates-with-street-party/ |title=Comedian dreams up genius way to dodge York parking fine \u2013 celebrates with street party |date=6 November 2015 |website=YorkMix |access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Boss got [[Lord Mayor of Birmingham|Birmingham Lord Mayor]] [[Yvonne Mosquito]] to officially open his kitchen extension. At first Mosquito declined, as it was not a public event, but after Boss raffled four tickets to the event to the public she agreed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/uk-england-birmingham-48276732/lord-mayor-opens-joe-lycett-s-new-kitchen-extension|title=The lord mayor, a comedian and a kitchen|website=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-06-30}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a legal dispute between fashion company [[Hugo Boss]] and the Swansea-based [[Boss Brewing]], Joe Lycett changed his name by [[deed poll]] in February 2020 from Joe Lycett to Hugo Boss. He said that he was drawing attention to fashion company [[Hugo Boss]]'s use of legal action and [[cease and desist]] letters relating to alleged [[copyright violations]] against numerous [[Small and medium-sized enterprises|small businesses]], including Boss Brewing, for use of the word 'Boss'.<ref name=\"HugoBBC\"/><ref>{{cite news|URL=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/comedy/news/joe-lycett-hugo-boss-name-change-deed-poll-cease-desist-twitter-fashion-a9367401.html|work=[[The Independent]]|title=Joe Lycett changes name to Hugo Boss in protest against fashion house|first=Jacob|last=Stolworthy|date=1 March 2020}}</ref> In the next series of ''Joe Lycett's Got Your Back'' (released in April 2020), the comedian launched a fake [[fashion show]] celebrating the release of a [[wrist bandage]] under the name 'Hugo Boss' outside the flagship store of the fashion company with the same name in Regent's Street, London.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mangan |first1=Lucy |title=Joe Lycett's Got Your Back review \u2013 will the real Hugo Boss please stand up! |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/apr/10/joe-lycetts-got-your-back-review-channel-4 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Boss claims that the Hugo Boss, the company, called the police following this incident.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Williams |first1=Kathryn |title=Joe Lycett's takedown of Hugo Boss aired tonight and it was brilliant |url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/tv/joe-lycetts-takedown-hugo-boss-18073883 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=walesonline |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ List of television performances\n|-\n! Year \n! Title \n! Role \n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Epic Win'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| August \u2013 September 2011\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Dirty Digest''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| November 2011\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats]]'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 14\n|-\n|2012\n|''[[Deal or No Deal (British game show)|Celebrity Deal Or No Deal]]''\n|Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n|Won \u00a335,000 for his selected charity after choosing box number 16\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Celebrity Juice]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 8\n|-\n| 2012\u20132014\n| ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 26 (2012), Series 28 (2014)\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015\n| ''[[Virtually Famous]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 1 (2014), Series 2 (2015)\n|-\n| 2014\u20132016\n| ''[[Live at the Apollo (TV series)|Live At The Apollo]]'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 10 (2014), Series 12 (2016)\n|-\n| 2014\u20132017\n| ''[[8 Out of 10 Cats Does Countdown]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| \n|-\n|-\n| 2015\u20132017\n| ''[[Would I Lie to You? (TV series)|Would I Lie To You?]]'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 3 (2015), Series 5 (2017)\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Alan Davies: As Yet Untitled]]'' \n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 3 (2015)\n|-\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Insert Name Here]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 1 (2016)\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Taskmaster (TV series)|Taskmaster]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 4 (2017)\n|-\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Roast Battle]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 1 (2018)\n|-\n|-\n| 2018\n|| ''The Time It Takes''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n| Series 1 (2018)\n|-\n|-\n| 2019\n|| ''[[The Great British Sewing Bee]]''\n| Presenter<br />\n| [[The Great British Sewing Bee (series 5)|Series 5]] (2019)\n|-\n|-\n| 2019-2020\n|| ''Joe Lycett\u2019s Got Your Back'' <br/>''Hugo Boss's Got Your Back'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joelycett/status/1235869925102804992|title=Filmed this last night. It\u2019s a lot of fun. Coming to @Channel4 next month. pic.twitter.com/cJQQKME4WS|last=Boss|first=Hugo|date=2020-03-06|website=@joelycett|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n| Presenter<br />\n| Series 1 (2019), Series 2 (2020)\n|-\n|-\n| 2019\u20132020\n|| ''[[The Big Fat Quiz]]''\n| Himself (as Joe Lycett)\n|The Big Fat Quiz of Everything (2019 Special),<br/>The Big Fat Quiz of the Decade (2020)\n|}\n\n== Stand-up DVDs ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Release Date !! Age Rating\n|-\n| ''Joe Lycett: That's The Way A-Ha A-Ha, Joe Lycett \u2013 Live'' || 21 November 2016 || align=center|15\n|-\n| ''Joe Lycett: I'm About to Lose Control And I Think Joe Lycett \u2013 Live'' || 26 November 2018 || align=center|15\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n \n==External links==\n*{{official website|http://www.joelycettcomedy.co.uk/}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=3899396|name=Joe Lycett}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Boss, Hugo}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:English television presenters]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT comedians]]\n[[Category:Bisexual men]]\n[[Category:Pansexual people]]\n[[Category:Bisexual rights activists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from England]]\n", "name_user": "Bangalamania", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Adding citation for quote.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Lycett"}
{"title_page": "The Queen's Wake", "text_new": "{{short description|1813 poem by James Hogg}}\n\n'''''The Queen's Wake''''' is a narrative poem by [[James Hogg]], first published in 1813. It consists of an Introduction, three Nights, and a Conclusion, totalling over five thousand lines, and there are also authorial notes. The poem presents the contributions, in various metres, of a series of Scottish bards to a competition organised by [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] on her arrival in Scotland from France in 1561.\n\n==Background==\nIn his 'Memoir of the Author's Life', revised in 1832, Hogg maintained that he was encouraged by his friend [[John Grieve (poet)|John Grieve]] to build on his earlier poetic achievements as he sought to begin a literary career in Edinburgh. He recalled that, recognising that what he had produced recently, including pieces  for his periodical ''[[The Spy (periodical by James Hogg)|The Spy]]'', consisted of ballads or metrical tales, Hogg decided that if he was to produce a long poem it would best consist of a collection of such shorter pieces:<ref>''Altrive Tales'', ed Gillian Hughes (Edinburgh, 2003), 28.</ref> from this came the idea of the framework afforded by a bardic competition staged by [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. 'Macgregor', sung by the eleventh bard, and 'King Edward's Dream', sung by the fifteenth, appeared in ''The Spy''.<ref>James Hogg, ''The Spy'', ed. Gillian Hughes (Edinburgh, 2000), 402\u201305 No. 40), 209\u201312 (No. 20).</ref> The bulk of ''The Queen's Wake'' was probably composed between March and September 1812.<ref>Gillian Hughes, ''James Hogg: A Life'' (Edinburgh, 2007), 109.</ref>\n\n==Editions==\n===First and second editions===\n''The Queen's Wake: A Legendary Poem, by James Hogg'' was first published by George Goldie in Edinburgh, and by [[Longman]], Hurst, Rees, Orme, and Brown, London on 30 January 1813.<ref>James Hogg, ''The Queen's Wake'', ed. Douglas S. Mack (Edinburgh, 2004)', xlix.</ref> On 14 June the same publishers re-issued the copies remaining unsold as a second edition, with replacement pages at the beginning and end.<ref>''Ibid.'', l.</ref>\n===Third and fourth editions===\nGoldie published a third edition, this time with [[Henry Colburn]] in London, on 14 July 1814:<ref>''Ibid.'', liii.</ref> for this Hogg made a number of changes, notably providing 'The Witch of Fife' with a happy ending at the suggestion of [[Walter Scott]]<ref>''Ibid.'', liii\u2013liv.</ref> and modernising the language of 'Kilmeny'. Goldie then became bankrupt, and the edition was re-issued as the fourth on 15 December 1814 published by [[William Blackwood]] in Edinburgh and [[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]] in London.<ref>''Ibid.'', lxiii.</ref>\n===Fifth and sixth editions===\nIn 1819 a fifth edition, carefully revised by Hogg from the third, notably expanding the portraits of the eighth, ninth, and eleventh bards, appeared with illustrations aimed at a subscription readership. It was published by Blackwood and Murray and accompanied by a sixth edition using the same type but smaller sheets.<ref>''Ibid.'', lxx.</ref>\n===Critical edition===\nA critical edition, by Douglas S. Mack, appeared as a volume in the Stirling/South Carolina Research Edition of the Complete Works of James Hogg published by Edinburgh University Press in 2004. This presents emended texts of the first and fifth editions.\n\n==Summary==\n''Introduction''\n\nOn her arrival in Scotland, Mary Queen of Scots summons the nation's bards to a competition at Christmas [1813: at Easter].\n\n''Night the First''\n\nIn 'Malcolm of Lorn', the first bard, Rizzio, sings elaborately of a youth who dies of grief as his beloved returns from a prolonged residence abroad with her father.\n\nIn 'Young Kennedy', the second bard, Gardyn, sings of Kennedy's seduction of Matilda and murder of her father, whose spirit haunts their marriage bed.\n\nIn 'The Witch of Fife', the eighth bard, from Leven, sings of an old man who follows his wife and other witches to Carlisle to drink the bishop's wine. [n 1813 he is burnt alive, in 1819 rescued by his wife.]\n\n''Night the Second''\n\nIn 'Glen-Avin', the ninth bard, Farquhar of Spey, sings of a sage who dies defying the Spirit of the Storm in the Cairngorms.\n\nIn 'Old David', the tenth bard, from Hogg's Ettrick, sings of the rescue by David and his seven sons of the beloved of one of them from a cave where she is imprisoned by marauders taken to be fairies.\n\nThe eleventh bard, from Lomond, sings 'The Spectre's Cradle-Song' and 'Macgregor', the latter telling of the eponymous warrior's abduction by a mysterious fatal woman.\n\nIn 'Earl Walter', the twelfth bard, from Clyde, sings of Walter Hamilton's defeating Lord Darcie in single combat before the king.\n\nIn  'Kilmeny', the thirteenth bard, Drummond of Ern, sings of a young woman who is taken to 'the land of thochte' and returns for a period to impart 'wordis of wonder, and wordis of truthe'.\n\n''Night the Third''\n\nIn 'Mary Scott', the fourteenth bard, from the Borders, sings of how Lord Pringle of Torwoodlee disguises himself as an abbot to visit his beloved Mary, daughter of his rival Tushilaw. When their liaison is discovered, her mother poisons her, but after his forces have triumphed Lord Pringle restores her to life with a kiss, they marry, and peace prevails.\n\nIn 'King Edward's Dream', the fifteenth bard, from Lammermoor, sings of the dying Edward I's vision of a future free Scotland entering into a voluntary union with England.\n\nIn 'Drumlanrig', the sixteenth bard, from Nithsdale, sings of the defeat of the Earl of Lennox's invading force by James Douglas of Drumlanrig. Douglas is encouraged by May Morison, who had been abducted by the English and whose brother falls in the conflict, and at the end he takes her as his bride.\n\nIn 'The Abbot M'Kinnon', the seventeenth bard, from the Hebrides, sings of the sinking of the Abbot of Iona's ship in retribution for his liaison with Matilda of Skye in male disguise.\n\n''Conclusion''\n\nAfter a passionate debate between the factions at Court, Queen Mary's harp is awarded to Gardyn. The Ettrick bard is happy to receive a less elaborate instrument, which will eventually be inherited by Hogg.\n\n==Reception==\nThe first edition of ''The Queen's Wake'' was enthusiastically received by almost all of the reviewers as a triumph by a self-taught genius. The only dissenting voice was ''[[The Eclectic Review]]'', which objected to the modern obsession with supernatural beings.<ref>''The Eclectic Review'', 9 (June 1813), 647\u201253 (647).</ref> The third edition was boosted by a favourable review by [[Francis Jeffrey]] in ''The [[Edinburgh Review]]'', recognising poetry of a high order,<ref>''The Edinburgh Review'', 24 (November 1814), 157\u201274</ref> though elsewhere there were less sympathetic verdicts.<ref>Mack, ''op. cit.'', lxiv\u2012lxv.</ref> \n\n==References==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1813 poems]]\n[[Category:Scottish poetry]]\n[[Category:poems by James Hogg]]\n[[Category:Romantic poets]]\n[[Category:Mary, Queen of Scots]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1813 poem by James Hogg}}\n\n'''''The Queen's Wake''''' is a narrative poem by [[James Hogg]], first published in 1813. It consists of an Introduction, three Nights, and a Conclusion, totalling over five thousand lines, and there are also authorial notes. The poem presents the contributions, in various metres, of a series of Scottish bards to a competition organised by [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] on her arrival in Scotland from France in 1561.\n\n==Background==\nIn his 'Memoir of the Author's Life', revised in 1832, Hogg maintained that he was encouraged by his friend [[John Grieve (poet)|John Grieve]] to build on his earlier poetic achievements as he sought to begin a literary career in Edinburgh. He recalled that, recognising that what he had produced recently, including pieces  for his periodical ''[[The Spy (periodical by James Hogg)|The Spy]]'', consisted of ballads or metrical tales, Hogg decided that if he was to produce a long poem it would best consist of a collection of such shorter pieces:<ref>''Altrive Tales'', ed Gillian Hughes (Edinburgh, 2003), 28.</ref> from this came the idea of the framework afforded by a bardic competition staged by [[Mary, Queen of Scots]]. 'Macgregor', sung by the eleventh bard, and 'King Edward's Dream', sung by the fifteenth, appeared in ''The Spy''.<ref>James Hogg, ''The Spy'', ed. Gillian Hughes (Edinburgh, 2000), 402\u201305 No. 40), 209\u201312 (No. 20).</ref> The bulk of ''The Queen's Wake'' was probably composed between March and September 1812.<ref>Gillian Hughes, ''James Hogg: A Life'' (Edinburgh, 2007), 109.</ref>\n\n==Editions==\n===First and second editions===\n''The Queen's Wake: A Legendary Poem, by James Hogg'' was first published by George Goldie in Edinburgh, and by [[Longman]], Hurst, Rees, Orme, and Brown, London on 30 January 1813.<ref>James Hogg, ''The Queen's Wake'', ed. Douglas S. Mack (Edinburgh, 2004)', xlix.</ref> On 14 June the same publishers re-issued the copies remaining unsold as a second edition, with replacement pages at the beginning and end.<ref>''Ibid.'', l.</ref>\n===Third and fourth editions===\nGoldie published a third edition, this time with [[Henry Colburn]] in London, on 14 July 1814:<ref>''Ibid.'', liii.</ref> for this Hogg made a number of changes, notably providing 'The Witch of Fife' with a happy ending at the suggestion of [[Walter Scott]]<ref>''Ibid.'', liii\u2013liv.</ref> and modernising the language of 'Kilmeny'. Goldie then became bankrupt, and the edition was re-issued as the fourth on 15 December 1814 published by [[William Blackwood]] in Edinburgh and [[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]] in London.<ref>''Ibid.'', lxiii.</ref>\n===Fifth and sixth editions===\nIn 1819 a fifth edition, carefully revised by Hogg from the third, notably expanding the portraits of the eighth, ninth, and eleventh bards, appeared with illustrations aimed at a subscription readership. It was published by Blackwood and Murray and accompanied by a sixth edition using the same type but smaller sheets.<ref>''Ibid.'', lxx.</ref>\n===Critical edition===\nA critical edition, by Douglas S. Mack, appeared as a volume in the Stirling/South Carolina Research Edition of the Complete Works of James Hogg published by Edinburgh University Press in 2004. This presents emended texts of the first and fifth editions.\n\n==Summary==\n''Introduction''\n\nOn her arrival in Scotland, Mary Queen of Scots summons the nation's bards to a competition at Christmas [1813: at Easter].\n\n''Night the First''\n\nIn 'Malcolm of Lorn', the first bard, Rizzio, sings elaborately of a youth who dies of grief as his beloved returns from a prolonged residence abroad with her father.\n\nIn 'Young Kennedy', the second bard, Gardyn, sings of Kennedy's seduction of Matilda and murder of her father, whose spirit haunts their marriage bed.\n\nIn 'The Witch of Fife', the eighth bard, from Leven, sings of an old man who follows his wife and other witches to Carlisle to drink the bishop's wine. [n 1813 he is burnt alive, in 1819 rescued by his wife.]\n\n''Night the Second''\n\nIn 'Glen-Avin', the ninth bard, Farquhar of Spey, sings of a sage who dies defying the Spirit of the Storm in the Cairngorms.\n\nIn 'Old David', the tenth bard, from Hogg's Ettrick, sings of the rescue by David and his seven sons of the beloved of one of them from a cave where she is imprisoned by marauders taken to be fairies.\n\nThe eleventh bard, from Lomond, sings 'The Spectre's Cradle-Song' and 'Macgregor', the latter telling of the eponymous warrior's abduction by a mysterious fatal woman.\n\nIn 'Earl Walter', the twelfth bard, from Clyde, sings of Walter Hamilton's defeating Lord Darcie in single combat before the king.\n\nIn  'Kilmeny', the thirteenth bard, Drummond of Ern, sings of a young woman who is taken to 'the land of thochte' and returns for a period to impart 'wordis of wonder, and wordis of truthe'.\n\n''Night the Third''\n\nIn 'Mary Scott', the fourteenth bard, from the Borders, sings of how Lord Pringle of Torwoodlee disguises himself as an abbot to visit his beloved Mary, daughter of his rival Tushilaw. When their liaison is discovered, her mother poisons her, but after his forces have triumphed Lord Pringle restores her to life with a kiss, they marry, and peace prevails.\n\nIn 'King Edward's Dream', the fifteenth bard, from Lammermoor, sings of the dying Edward I's vision of a future free Scotland entering into a voluntary union with England.\n\nIn 'Drumlanrig', the sixteenth bard, from Nithsdale, sings of the defeat of the Earl of Lennox's invading force by James Douglas of Drumlanrig. Douglas is encouraged by May Morison, who had been abducted by the English and whose brother falls in the conflict, and at the end he takes her as his bride.\n\nIn 'The Abbot M'Kinnon', the seventeenth bard, from the Hebrides, sings of the sinking of the Abbot of Iona's ship in retribution for his liaison with Matilda of Skye in male disguise.\n\n''Conclusion''\n\nAfter a passionate debate between the factions at Court, Queen Mary's harp is awarded to Gardyn. The Ettrick bard is happy to receive a less elaborate instrument, which will eventually be inherited by Hogg.\n\n==Reception==\nThe first edition of ''The Queen's Wake'' was enthusiastically received by almost all of the reviewers as a triumph by a self-taught genius. The only dissenting voice was ''[[The Eclectic Review]]'', which objected to the modern obsession with supernatural beings.<ref>''The Eclectic Review'', 9 (June 1813), 647\u201253 (647).</ref> The third edition was boosted by a favourable review by [[Francis Jeffrey]] in ''The [[Edinburgh Review]]'', recognising poetry of a high order,<ref>''The Edinburgh Review'', 24 (November 1814), 157\u201274</ref> though elsewhere there were less sympathetic verdicts.<ref>Mack, ''op. cit.'', lxiv\u2012lxv.</ref> \n\n