{"title_page": "James Bloom", "text_new": "{{For|the English clergyman and antiquary|James Harvey Bloom}}\n{{short description|British screenwriter}}\n'''James Bloom''' (born 1975) is a [[screenwriter]], [[Film director|director]] and [[creative director]] known for his work in television, advertising and online entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm8344357|title=James Bloom|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> He is the grandson of [[Freddy Bloom]] [[OBE]].\n\n==Career==\nHe was one of the youngest [[journalists]] at [[The Guardian]] newspaper,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/jamesbloom |title=James Bloom |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/guardian/results.html?st=advanced&QryTxt=%22james+bloom%22&type=historic&sortby=RELEVANCE&datetype=6&frommonth=10&fromday=01&fromyear=1994&tomonth=07&today=31&toyear=2003&By=&Title=&publications=ALL |title=The Guardian and Observer : Archives |website=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> writing from the age of 19 and a [[Contributing editor|Contributing Editor]] at [[GQ]] magazine from the age of 20. He also worked on the launch of Wired magazine in the UK<ref>{{cite news|author=Dominic Cavendish |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/network-the-virtual-state-of-the-art-1613021.html |title=NETWORK : The virtual state of the art |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> with [[Tony Ageh]] [[OBE]]. He joined Ageh to launch [[Virgin.net]], a leading ISP and entertainment channel subsequently bought out by cable TV provider [[NTL Incorporated]].\n\nHe worked as a creative at advertising agency Lateral,<ref name=\"campaignlive1\">{{cite web|author=Camilla Palmer |url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/campaign-i-static-creates-future-intelligence-division/33292 |title=CAMPAIGN-I: Static creates future intelligence division |website=Campaignlive.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> creating award-winning campaigns for Levi's and Nationwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/yahoo-looks-follow-up-levi-s-error-adverts/128018 |title=Yahoo! looks to follow-up on Levi&#39;s &#34;error&#34; adverts. |website=Campaignlive.co.uk |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> He played a key role in the creation of the leading digital TV channel [[PlayJam]] at Static2358,<ref name=\"campaignlive1\"/> sold to OpenTV for $59 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/opentv-buys-static-59m/13719?src_site=brandrepublic |title=OpenTV buys Static for $59m |website=Campaignlive.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref>\n\nWorking with [[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]] creator [[Tim Kring]], he wrote and directed the online series '[[Conspiracy For Good]]'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1857517|title=The Conspiracy for Good: London 2010 |website=IMDb.com|accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> The influential series received 9 million views online. His comedy viral 'Bass Jump'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5947856|title=Bass Jump (2010)|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> received 1.5 million views and positioned No. 6 in Go Viral's chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.mediamobz.com/web-video-industry-news/top-10-viral-videos-september-2010-courtesy-of-goviral/ |title=Top 10 Viral Videos \u2013 September 2010 courtesy of GoViral &#124; MediaMobz |website=Blog.mediamobz.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> His advertising campaigns include work for [[Guinness]], [[American Express]], [[Barclaycard]], [[Intel]] and [[Google]].\n\nHis comedy film 'Love Your Neighbour' was funded by [[Working Title Films]] and the [[British Council]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/love-your-neighbour |title=British Council Film: Love Your Neighbour |website=Film.britishcouncil.org |date=2005-11-26 |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> appearing at [[Edinburgh International Film Festival]], [[Berlin International Film Festival]], [[Portobello Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portobellofilmfestival.com/2003/08west.html |title=PFF 2003 |website=Portobellofilmfestival.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> and winning High Commendation at the [[TCM Classic Shorts Film Competition]].\n\nBloom's screenplays have won a number of international screenwriting awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodscreenplaycontest.com/contest/past-winners/2015-winners|title=Hollywood Screenplay Contest|website=Hollywoodscreenplaycontest.com|accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pageawards.com/past-winners/2018-winners/2018-finalists|title=The 2018 PAGE Awards Finalists|website=pageawards.com/|accessdate=2018-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pageawards.com/past-winners/2015-winners/2015-semi-finalists/ |title=2015 Semi-Finalists &#124; PAGE International Screenwriting Awards: Screenplay Contests |website=Pageawards.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thescreenwritingawards.com/winners/ |title=Winners \u2014 The West Field Screenwriting Awards |website=Thescreenwritingawards.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moviebytes.com/ContestDetail.cfm?tab=tab3&ContestNumber=2905&StoryID=7255|title=ScreenCraft Names Fellowship Finalists (/ContestDetail.cfm/tab=tab3&ContestNumber=2905&StoryID=7255)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenplayfestival.com/?cat=17|title=Contest Results - SCREENPLAY FESTIVAL|website=screenplayfestival.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bloom, James}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British film directors]]\n[[Category:British male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:British television directors]]\n[[Category:Creative directors]]\n[[Category:The Guardian journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the English clergyman and antiquary|James Harvey Bloom}}\n{{short description|British screenwriter}}\n'''James Bloom''' (born 1975) is a [[screenwriter]], [[Film director|director]] and [[creative director]] known for his work in television, advertising and online entertainment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm8344357|title=James Bloom|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> He is the grandson of [[Freddy Bloom]] [[OBE]].\n\n==Career==\nHe was one of the youngest [[journalists]] at [[The Guardian]] newspaper<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/jamesbloom |title=James Bloom |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/guardian/results.html?st=advanced&QryTxt=%22james+bloom%22&type=historic&sortby=RELEVANCE&datetype=6&frommonth=10&fromday=01&fromyear=1994&tomonth=07&today=31&toyear=2003&By=&Title=&publications=ALL |title=The Guardian and Observer : Archives |website=Pqasb.pqarchiver.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref>, writing from the age of 19 and a [[Contributing editor|Contributing Editor]] at [[GQ]] magazine from the age of 20. He also worked on the launch of Wired magazine in the UK<ref>{{cite news|author=Dominic Cavendish |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/network-the-virtual-state-of-the-art-1613021.html |title=NETWORK : The virtual state of the art |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> with [[Tony Ageh]] [[OBE]]. He joined Ageh to launch [[Virgin.net]], a leading ISP and entertainment channel subsequently bought out by cable TV provider [[NTL Incorporated]]. \n\nHe worked as a creative at advertising agency Lateral,<ref name=\"campaignlive1\">{{cite web|author=Camilla Palmer |url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/campaign-i-static-creates-future-intelligence-division/33292 |title=CAMPAIGN-I: Static creates future intelligence division |website=Campaignlive.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> creating award-winning campaigns for Levi's and Nationwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/yahoo-looks-follow-up-levi-s-error-adverts/128018 |title=Yahoo! looks to follow-up on Levi&#39;s &#34;error&#34; adverts. |website=Campaignlive.co.uk |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> He played a key role in the creation of the leading digital TV channel [[PlayJam]] at Static2358,<ref name=\"campaignlive1\"/> sold to OpenTV for $59 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/opentv-buys-static-59m/13719?src_site=brandrepublic |title=OpenTV buys Static for $59m |website=Campaignlive.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref>\n\nWorking with [[Heroes (U.S. TV series)|Heroes]] creator [[Tim Kring]], he wrote and directed the online series '[[Conspiracy For Good]]'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1857517|title=The Conspiracy for Good: London 2010 |website=IMDb.com|accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> The influential series received 9 million views online. His comedy viral 'Bass Jump'<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5947856|title=Bass Jump (2010)|website=IMDb.com|accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> received 1.5 million views and positioned No. 6 in Go Viral's chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.mediamobz.com/web-video-industry-news/top-10-viral-videos-september-2010-courtesy-of-goviral/ |title=Top 10 Viral Videos \u2013 September 2010 courtesy of GoViral &#124; MediaMobz |website=Blog.mediamobz.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> His advertising campaigns include work for [[Guinness]], [[American Express]], [[Barclaycard]], [[Intel]] and [[Google]].\n\nHis comedy film 'Love Your Neighbour' was funded by [[Working Title Films]] and the [[British Council]],<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/love-your-neighbour |title=British Council Film: Love Your Neighbour |website=Film.britishcouncil.org |date=2005-11-26 |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> appearing at [[Edinburgh International Film Festival]], [[Berlin International Film Festival]], [[Portobello Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.portobellofilmfestival.com/2003/08west.html |title=PFF 2003 |website=Portobellofilmfestival.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> and winning High Commendation at the [[TCM Classic Shorts Film Competition]].\n\nBloom's screenplays have won a number of international screenwriting awards <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodscreenplaycontest.com/contest/past-winners/2015-winners|title=Hollywood Screenplay Contest|website=Hollywoodscreenplaycontest.com|accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://pageawards.com/past-winners/2018-winners/2018-finalists|title=The 2018 PAGE Awards Finalists|website=pageawards.com/|accessdate=2018-12-03}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://pageawards.com/past-winners/2015-winners/2015-semi-finalists/ |title=2015 Semi-Finalists &#124; PAGE International Screenwriting Awards: Screenplay Contests |website=Pageawards.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thescreenwritingawards.com/winners/ |title=Winners \u2014 The West Field Screenwriting Awards |website=Thescreenwritingawards.com |date= |accessdate=2017-05-02}}</ref>  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moviebytes.com/ContestDetail.cfm?tab=tab3&ContestNumber=2905&StoryID=7255|title=ScreenCraft Names Fellowship Finalists (/ContestDetail.cfm/tab=tab3&ContestNumber=2905&StoryID=7255)|publisher=}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenplayfestival.com/?cat=17|title=Contest Results - SCREENPLAY FESTIVAL|website=screenplayfestival.com}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bloom, James}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British film directors]]\n[[Category:British male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:British television directors]]\n[[Category:Creative directors]]\n[[Category:The Guardian journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "ur