.uk |accessdate=25 February 2013}}</ref>\n|First Division\n|2||0||4||1|| || ||6||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!28!!0!!4!!1!! !! !!32!!1\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total{{sfn|Joyce|2004|p=182|ps=}}\n!681!!169!!52!!5!!7!!2!!740!!176\n|}\n\n===International statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Wales national football team|Wales national team]]<ref>{{NFT player|pid=19864|accessdate=10 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1895||2||0\n|-\n|1896||2||2\n|-\n|1897||3||2\n|-\n|1898||2||0\n|-\n|1899||1||0\n|-\n|1900||1||1\n|-\n|1901||2||0\n|-\n|1902||2||0\n|-\n|1903||3||0\n|-\n|1904||1||0\n|-\n|1905||2||1\n|-\n|1907||3||1\n|-\n|1908||2||0\n|-\n|1909||3||1\n|-\n|1910||0||0\n|-\n|1911||0||0\n|-\n|1912||0||0\n|-\n|1913||3||1\n|-\n|1914||3||0\n|-\n|1920||3||0\n|-\n!Total||39||10\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''Chirk'''\n*[[Welsh Cup]] (1): 1894\n\n'''Manchester City'''\n*[[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] (1): [[1898\u201399 Football League|1898\u201399]]\n*[[FA Cup]] (1): [[1904 FA Cup Final|1903\u201304]]\n\n'''Manchester United'''\n*[[Football League First Division|First Division]] (2): [[1907\u201308 Football League|1907\u201308]], [[1910\u201311 Football League|1910\u201311]]\n*[[FA Cup]] (1): [[1909 FA Cup Final|1908\u201309]]\n*[[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]] (2): [[1908 FA Charity Shield|1908]], [[1911 FA Charity Shield|1911]]\n\n===National team===\n'''Wales'''\n*[[British Home Championship]] (2): [[1906\u201307 British Home Championship|1907]], [[1919\u201320 British Home Championship|1920]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Football League 100 Legends]]: 1998 (inducted)\n*[[English Football Hall of Fame]]: 2007 (inducted)\n\n==References==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{citation |last=Brandon |first=Derek |title=A\u2013Z of Manchester Football: 100 Years of Rivalry |publisher=Boondoggle |year=1978}}\n*{{citation |last=Harding |first=John |title=Football Wizard: The Billy Meredith Story |publisher=[[Robson Books]] |year=1998 |isbn=1-86105-137-9}}\n*{{citation |last=James |first=Gary |title=The Official Manchester City Hall of Fame |publisher=Hamlyn |year=2005 |isbn=0-600-61282-1}}\n*{{citation |last=James |first=Gary |title=Manchester City&nbsp;\u2013 The Complete Record |publisher=Breedon |year=2006 |isbn=1-85983-512-0 }}\n*{{citation |last=James |first=Gary |title=Manchester&nbsp;\u2013 A Football History |publisher=James Ward |year=2008}}\n*{{citation |last=Joyce |first=Michael |title=Football League Players' Records 1888\u20131939 |year=2004 |publisher=Tony Brown |isbn=1-899468-67-6}}\n*{{citation |last=Kent |first=Jeff |title=Port Vale Personalities |publisher=Witan Books |year=1996 |isbn=0-9529152-0-0 |url=https://www.amazon.ca/Port-Vale-Personalities-Jeff-Kent/dp/0952915200}}\n*{{citation |last=Penney |first=Ian |title=The Maine Road Encyclopaedia |publisher=Mainstream |year=1995 |isbn=1-85158-710-1}}\n*{{citation |last=Ward |first=Andrew |title=The Manchester City Story |publisher=Breedon |year=1984 |isbn=0-907969-05-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Awards\n|fg=navy\n|bg=gold\n|list1=\n{{Manchester City F.C. Hall of Fame}}\n{{Football League 100 Legends}}\n{{English Football Hall of Fame}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meredith, Billy}}\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Chirk]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Wales international footballers]]\n[[Category:Chirk AAA F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Northwich Victoria F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. wartime guest players]]\n[[Category:Port Vale F.C. wartime guest players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:English Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Association football coaches]]\n[[Category:Association football players who received a testimonial]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Billy Meredith\n| image          = Billy meredith city.jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Meredith as a [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] player in 1903\n| fullname       = William Henry Meredith\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1874|7|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Chirk]], [[Denbighshire]], Wales\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1958|4|19|1874|7|30|df=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Withington]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| position       = [[Outside forward]]\n| youthyears1    = |youthclubs1 = Black Park\n| years1         = 1890\u20131892 |clubs1 = [[Chirk AAA F.C.|Chirk]]                       |caps1 =     |goals1 = \n| years2         = 1892\u20131894 |clubs2 = [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]] |caps2 = 11  |goals2 = 5\n| years3         = 1894\u20131906 |clubs3 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]       |caps3 = 339 |goals3 = 129\n| years4         = 1906\u20131921 |clubs4 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]   |caps4 = 303 |goals4 = 35\n| years5         = 1921\u20131924 |clubs5 = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]       |caps5 = 28  |goals5 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 681 |totalgoals = 169\n| nationalyears1 = 1895\u20131920 |nationalteam1 = [[Wales national football team|Wales]] |nationalcaps1 = 48 | nationalgoals1 = 11<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/wal-recintlp.html |title=Wales \u2013 Record International Players |first=Luis Fernando Passo |last=Alpuin |publisher=[[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation]] |date=20 February 2000 |accessdate=10 March 2009 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''William Henry Meredith''' (30 July 1874&nbsp;\u2013 19 April 1958) was a Welsh professional [[Association football|footballer]]. He was considered one of the early superstars of football due to his performances, notably for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.stretford-end.com/united-articles/billy-meredith-legend.html |title=Legends: Billy Meredith Player Profile |publisher=Stretford-end.com |accessdate=25 February 2009 }}</ref> He won each domestic trophy in the [[English football league system|English football league]] and gained 48 caps for [[Wales national football team|Wales]], for whom he scored 11 goals and won two [[British Home Championship]] titles. His favoured position was [[Outside forward|outside right]], and his key skills were dribbling, passing, crossing and shooting. A dedicated and extremely fit professional, his habit of chewing on a [[toothpick]] during games made him instantly recognisable.\n\nIn 27 seasons in [[the Football League]] from 1892 to 1924 (not including the four seasons lost to the First World War and the 1905\u201306 season in which he was banned for bribing an opposition player), he scored 176 goals in 740 league and cup appearances. He played for [[Chirk AAA F.C.|Chirk]], before joining [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]] in 1892. His career took off when he signed with Manchester City in 1894 and turned professional in January 1895. He captained the team to the club's first major honour, a 1\u20130 victory over [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] in the [[1904 FA Cup Final]]. He moved to Manchester United in May 1906 after being banned for bribing [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] half-back [[Alex Leake]] \u00a310 to lose a match. There he won the league title in 1907\u201308 and 1910\u201311, the FA Cup in [[1909 FA Cup Final|1909]], as well as two [[FA Community Shield|FA Charity Shield]]s. He also helped to set up the [[Players' Union]], which was a fore-runner of the [[Professional Footballers' Association]]. He returned to Manchester City in 1921 at the age of 47 and played a further 32 games before retiring in 1924, making him the oldest ever player for City, United and Wales. He later ran the Stretford Road Hotel and helped to coach the short-lived [[Manchester Central F.C.|Manchester Central]].\n\n==Early life==\nMeredith was born in 1874 in [[Chirk]], a small mining town in [[Denbighshire]], Wales, just south of [[Wrexham]]. He started work at [[Black Park]] [[Coal mining|Colliery]] as a [[pit pony]] driver at the age of 12.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=7|ps=}} His family were [[Primitive Methodism|Primitive Methodists]], and Meredith himself remained a lifelong [[Teetotalism|teetotaller]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=9|ps=}} He spent eight years working in the mines, and worked during a tough time for the industry, enduring a 25% pay cut which led to [[strike action]] in 1893; this experience helped to shape his political views, which would become significant later in his life.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=8|ps=}} An interest in football was kindled by his elder brothers. Elias, the eldest, was a [[Railroad engineer|train driver]] for the [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=8|ps=}} His work allowed him to take Meredith to watch professional teams such as [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=8|ps=}} Football was a keen pastime for the miners, and the standard of amateur teams from towns and villages in north east Wales was high as a result; [[Chirk AAA F.C.|Chirk]] won the [[Welsh Cup]] five times between 1887 and 1894, with miners making up a large proportion of the team.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=8|ps=}} All the Meredith brothers played football, but [[Sam Meredith|Sam]], two years older than Billy, was the first to make an impression. He left Chirk to attempt a professional career, and went on to play for [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] as a full-back.{{sfn|James|2005|p=88|ps=}}\n\nMeredith made his debut for the Chirk first team in September 1892.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=15|ps=}} The club played in [[The Combination]], a league which contained a mixture of town clubs and reserve teams of clubs from big cities.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=15|ps=}} At the end of his first season Meredith played in the 1893 Welsh Cup final, which Chirk lost 2\u20131 to [[Wrexham A.F.C.|Wrexham]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=17|ps=}} Meredith formed a solid understanding with inside-right [[William Owen (footballer, born 1862)|William Owen]], a former Wales international. Chirk withdrew from The Combination and entered only the Welsh league in 1893 due to low attendances caused by the coal miners' strike.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=16|ps=}} In an attempt to make ends meet, Meredith not only played for Chirk, but accepted an offer to play for Football League club [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]] as well, who gave him a small fee on top of his expenses.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=16|ps=}} Northwich were a struggling side, who withdrew from [[the Football League]] at the end of the [[1893\u201394 Football League|1893\u201394]] season after finishing bottom of the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]]. The club won just three league matches; Meredith featured in each win.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=16|ps=}} Back at Chirk, Meredith gained his first honour as part of the team that beat Westminster Rovers to win the 1894 Welsh Cup.{{sfn|Ward|1984|ps=}}\n\n==Club career==\n\n===First spell at Manchester City===\nMeredith's performances for Northwich gained the attention of several other clubs in [[the Football League]]. [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] full-back [[Di Jones]], a former Chirk player, spoke with him about a possible move, but Bolton secretary [[John Bentley (football manager)|J.J. Bentley]] felt Meredith was too inexperienced and his frame too slight.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=22|ps=}} [[Lawrence Furniss]], an official at [[Manchester City F.C.|Ardwick]], had first noticed him while refereeing a Northwich match.{{sfn|James|2005|p=88|ps=}} Meredith also played in both meetings between the clubs that season.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=23|ps=}} Later in 1894, Ardwick, by then known as Manchester City, vigorously pursued Meredith's signature. Two club officials travelled to Wales to meet the player. One was secretary-manager [[Joshua Parlby]], the other either Furniss or chairman John Chapman.{{sfn|James|2005|p=88|ps=}}{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=23|ps=}} The pair were met with suspicion. Anecdotes by contemporary figures suggest they were initially chased away by locals, and were only allowed to speak to Meredith after they bought drinks for his mining colleagues.{{sfn|James|2005|p=88|ps=}} Meredith did not wish to abandon life in Chirk. His mother was particularly against the idea: \"It is all very well for you gentlemen to leave your big cities and come to our villages to steal our boys away&nbsp;... Our boys are happy and healthy, satisfied with their work and innocent amusements&nbsp;... if Billy takes my advice he will stick to his work and play football for his own amusement when work is finished.\"{{sfn|James|2005|p=88|ps=}} Meredith did eventually sign for Manchester City, but as an amateur.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=22|ps=}} He continued to work at the pit for at least a year, commuting back and forth for matches.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=23|ps=}}\n\nMeredith made his Manchester City debut in November 1894 in a 5\u20134 loss to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].{{sfn|Penney|1995|p=139|ps=}} The following week he played his first home match for the club at [[Hyde Road Football Stadium|Hyde Road]], and scored two goals against Newton Heath&nbsp;\u2013 who later became [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]&nbsp;\u2013 in the first [[Manchester derby]] to take place in the league. Newton Heath won the match 5\u20132. He turned professional in January 1895,{{sfn|Penney|1995|p=139|ps=}} and ended the [[1894\u201395 Manchester City F.C. season|1894\u201395]] season with 12 goals in 18 appearances, just three strikes behind top-scorer [[Pat Finnerhan]], who had played an extra 12 games.\n\nIn his [[1895\u201396 Manchester City F.C. season|first full season]] at Manchester City, Meredith finished as top scorer.{{sfn|James|2006|p=277}} He was appointed club captain in his [[1896\u201397 Manchester City F.C. season|second season]] at the club, aged just 21.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=34|ps=}} The club finished as [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] runners-up in [[1895\u201396 Manchester City F.C. season|1895\u201396]], but were denied promotion after heavy defeats to [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Birmingham City F.C.|Small Heath]] in the [[playoffs|test matches]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=39|ps=}} After the departure of strike partner Pat Finnerhan to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in March 1897, Meredith remained as City's star player.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=36|ps=}}\n\nHis new partner for the [[1897\u201398 Manchester City F.C. season|1897\u201398]] season was [[Stockport Smith|William Smith]] (known as \"Stockport Smith\" to differentiate him from another William Smith in the team), whilst [[Billie Gillespie]] was placed at centre-forward.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=41|ps=}} Meredith provided Gillespie with many crosses into the box,{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=41|ps=}} picking up numerous assists as Gillespie outscored Meredith by 19 goals to 12. Meredith also acted as a mentor for the slightly younger Gillespie, steering him away from drinking sessions by taking him along on fishing trips.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=42|ps=}} The final match of the season saw Meredith score his first [[hat-trick]] for the club in an emphatic 9\u20130 win against [[Burton Swifts F.C.|Burton Swifts]].{{sfn|James|2006|pp=280\u201328|ps=}}\n{{Quote box|quote=\"Oh I wish I was you Billy Meredith<br />I wish I was you, I envy you, indeed I do!<br />It ain't that you're tricky with your feet,<br />But it's those centres that you send in<br />Which Turnbull then heads in,<br />Oh, I wish I was you,<br />Indeed I do<br />Indeed I do\"|source=\u2014 One of the popular songs sung on the terraces at Hyde Road.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=82|ps=}}|width=20%|align=right}}\n\nCity dominated the Second Division in the [[1898\u201399 Manchester City F.C. season|1898\u201399]] season, and won promotion as champions.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=42|ps=}} Helping them to keep them in winning ways in the close season was late signing [[Jimmy Ross (footballer born 1866)|Jimmy Ross]], a veteran forward who Meredith considered to be his \"favourite hero\".{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=42|ps=}} Meredith claimed 30 goals in 35 games, including hat-tricks against [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]], [[Loughborough F.C.|Loughborough]], [[Darwen F.C.|Darwen]] and [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]].\n\nMeredith scored City's first goal in the [[Football League First Division|First Division]] on the opening day of the [[1899\u20131900 Manchester City F.C. season|1899\u20131900]] season in a 4\u20133 defeat to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] at [[Ewood Park]] on 2 September.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=45|ps=}} Seven days later he claimed two goals in a 4\u20130 home victory over [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], and \"led the field that day\" by dribbling the ball almost the whole length of the pitch before launching a powerful shot that settled into the corner of [[Jack Fryer (footballer born 1877)|Jack Fryer's]] net.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=45|ps=}} The ''[[Athletic News]]'' reported that \"for real brilliance the right-wing [Meredith and Ross] took the biscuit\".{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=46|ps=}}\n\nFirst Division defences managed to limit Meredith's contribution in the [[1900\u201301 Manchester City F.C. season|1900\u201301]] campaign by singling him out for rough treatment, though [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] manager [[Tom Watson (football manager)|Tom Watson]] felt compelled to write a letter to Manchester City denying that a Liverpool director had stated that \"all that the opposition had to do was watch Meredith \u2013 the rest are no good\".{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=61|ps=}} He finished the season with just seven goals in 35 appearances.\n\nMeredith found the net eight times in 38 games in the [[1901\u201302 Manchester City F.C. season|1901\u201302]] campaign, as City were relegated back out of the First Division. The club's secretary, [[Sam Ormerod]], selected 29 different players as the club slumped to defeat in 13 of the opening 20 games.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=62|ps=}} Ormerod was forced to step down, as new business figures took control behind the scenes and began to sign promising young Scottish players.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=66|ps=}} New manager [[Tom Maley]] was more willing than his predecessor to confront Meredith over his tendency to stray out of position and attempt to dominate the City attack.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=67|ps=}}\n\nCity won immediate promotion as Second Division champions in [[1902\u201303 Manchester City F.C. season|1902\u201303]], with Meredith scoring 22 goals in 37 appearances and claiming a hat-trick against [[Chesterfield F.C.|Chesterfield Town]]. Maley managed to find him a suitable inside-right partner in [[Jimmy Bannister]], who was unselfish in his play and willing to feed the ball through to Meredith.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=69|ps=}} He also played [[Sammy Frost]] at half-back, who was able to win the ball and bring Meredith into the play, and signed outside-left [[Frank Booth (footballer)|Frank Booth]] to balance the attack.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=71|ps=}} Maley encouraged teamwork, meaning there was less pressure on Meredith from opposition defenders.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=71|ps=}}\n\nMeredith was partnered with [[George Livingstone]] for the [[1903\u201304 Manchester City F.C. season|1903\u201304]] campaign, who was able to supply him and the rest of the team with quality passes.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=71|ps=}} Drawn against a strong [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] outfit in the First Round of the [[FA Cup]], Meredith was the \"raider-in-chief\" as City claimed a 3\u20132 victory at Hyde Road.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=76|ps=}} City then defeated [[Arsenal F.C.|Woolwich Arsenal]] and [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] to reach the semi-finals.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=78|ps=}} There they faced [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|The Wednesday]] at [[Goodison Park]], and Meredith scored one goal (bundled in by Gillespie) and claimed two assists as City won the game 3\u20131.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=79|ps=}} Their opponents in [[1904 FA Cup Final|the final]] at [[Crystal Palace National Sports Centre|Crystal Palace]] were mid-table Second Division outfit [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]], and Meredith was cautiously optimistic before the match, stating \"We ought to win&nbsp;... if we play anything like our normal game the cup is ours&nbsp;... but this is the cup final and, well, anything might happen.\"{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=85|ps=}} With just over 20 minutes played, Livingstone found Meredith with a long ball, who then beat goalkeeper [[Dai Davies (footballer born 1880)|Dai Davies]] to score the only goal of the game; Bolton supporters long maintained that Meredith had been offside.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=90|ps=}} As captain, Meredith was handed the trophy by Prime Minister [[Arthur Balfour]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=94|ps=}}\n\nHe scored nine goals in 36 games in the [[1904\u201305 Manchester City F.C. season|1904\u201305]] season, as City came within two points and two places of champions [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]. The season ended in controversial circumstances at [[Villa Park]], and with a 3\u20132 defeat to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] ending any hopes of winning the league, [[Sandy Turnbull]] and Villa captain [[Alex Leake]] exchanged blows.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=105|ps=}} [[The Football Association]] launched [[English football bribery scandal|an investigation into the violence]], and the findings shocked the sporting world as Meredith was suspended for the entirety of the [[1905\u201306 Manchester City F.C. season|1905\u201306]] season for (unsuccessfully) attempting to bribe Alex Leake.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=110|ps=}} No evidence was taken from Meredith, who denied the charge, and the evidence was not made public.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=111|ps=}} The club, fearful of FA sanctions, refused to pay Meredith during the campaign. He was transfer listed in May 1906 after he claimed that he had only attempted to bribe Leake on the orders of manager Tom Maley and that illegal payments were common practice at Hyde Road.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=117|ps=}} The FA acted on his information, and fined Manchester City \u00a3900 for illegal payments and suspended numerous players, boardroom members and staff members.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=116|ps=}}\n\n{{Quote|You approve of the severe punishment administered by the Commission AGAINST ME and state that the offence I committed at Aston Villa should have wiped me out of football forever. Why ME ALONE? when I was only the spokesman of others equally guilty.|Meredith wrote an open letter to the ''Athletic News'', justifying his decision to reveal the illegal actions of the club.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=118|ps=}}}}\n\n===Manchester United===\n[[File:Billymeredith.jpg|thumb|right|Meredith in Manchester United colours]]\nIn May 1906, while still serving his ban, Meredith moved to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. He joined on a free transfer and received a \u00a3500 signing-on fee from United; Manchester City reluctantly accepted the transfer as they had previously signed an undertaking promising Meredith a benefit match, and he was willing to forego on the agreement if the club instead granted his transfer.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=122|ps=}} He returned from suspension on 1 January 1907, and marked his debut at [[Bank Street (football ground)|Bank Street]] with an assist for [[Sandy Turnbull]] to score the only goal of the game against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=150|ps=}} In addition to Turnbull, Meredith was joined at United by former City teammates [[Jimmy Bannister]] and [[Herbert Burgess]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=155|ps=}} This new forward line made the team into a powerful force, as they already possessed a dominant half-back line in captain [[Charlie Roberts]], [[Dick Duckworth (footballer born 1882)|Dick Duckworth]] and [[Alex Bell]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=154|ps=}} They ended the [[1906\u201307 Manchester United F.C. season|1906\u201307]] season in eighth place in the [[Football League First Division|First Division]].\n\nManager [[Ernest Mangnall]] signed [[Jimmy Turnbull]], and the forward line of Meredith, Bannister, Jimmy Turnbull and Sandy Turnbull were dominant in the [[1907\u201308 Manchester United F.C. season|1907\u201308]] campaign.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=156|ps=}} United won the title with a nine-point margin over second-placed [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], and secured the [[1908 FA Charity Shield]] (the first ever [[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]]) with a 4\u20130 win over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]].\n\nUnited slipped to a disappointing 13th-place finish in [[1908\u201309 Manchester United F.C. season|1908\u201309]]. Meredith was suspended for the month of January in punishment for kicking a [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] player in an [[FA Cup]] match.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=162|ps=}} The club reached the [[1909 FA Cup Final]], knocking out Brighton, [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]], [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] and [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]. Their cup final opponents at [[Crystal Palace National Sports Centre|Crystal Palace]] were [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]], captained at centre-half by [[Billy Wedlock]] \u2013 [[England national football team|England]] captain and staunch opponent of the [[Players' Union]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=165|ps=}} A Sandy Turnbull goal settled the tie, which was described as quite a boring game; Meredith himself dismissed reports of the match, stating \"it was a good game for dashing, keen, thrilling football, great goalkeeping and narrow escapes at either end\".{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=166|ps=}} Meredith and his teammates celebrated the victory with [[music hall]] stars such as [[George Robey]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=171|ps=}}\n\nUnited finished fifth in [[1909\u201310 Manchester United F.C. season|1909\u201310]] and exited the FA Cup at the First Round with a defeat to [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] at [[Turf Moor]]. However the club continued to advance under the generous chairmanship of [[John Henry Davies]], and [[Old Trafford]] was opened in February 1910.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=172|ps=}}\n\n[[Harold Halse]] was to partner Meredith at inside-right for the [[1910\u201311 Manchester United F.C. season|1910\u201311]] season, but proved too much of a \"free-spirit\" and was replaced by [[Jack Picken]], a \"plodder [who] understands what Meredith requires\".{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=181|ps=}} A defeat at [[Villa Park]] in the penultimate game of the season left United needing to beat third-place [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and hope that Aston Villa failed to beat [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=182|ps=}} United were a goal down when Meredith provided [[Enoch West]] with a cross which West sent into the net for the equalising goal.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=182|ps=}} Four more goals came and they won the game 5\u20131 and left the field as champions of England for the second time.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=182|ps=}}\n\nMeredith played in the [[1911 FA Charity Shield]], as United beat [[Swindon Town F.C.|Swindon Town]] 8\u20134 at Stamford Bridge. However the [[1911\u201312 Manchester United F.C. season|1911\u201312]] campaign ended in a disappointing 13th-place finish and Mangnall left the club to manage [[Manchester derby|rivals]] [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. Meredith's [[Benefit (sports)|Benefit]] match was played on 7 September 1912, between Manchester United and Manchester City, and the [[Football Association of Wales|Welsh FA]] also donated the proceeds of two trial matches to the fund.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=185|ps=}} There were 39,911 spectators and a total of \u00a31,400 was raised.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=186|ps=}}\n\nNew manager [[John Bentley (football manager)|John Bentley]] led United to a fourth-place finish in [[1912\u201313 Manchester United F.C. season|1912\u201313]]. He dropped Meredith to blood a young [[Jackie Sheldon]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=191|ps=}} By this time, Meredith made headlines primarily due to his squabbling with the club over them stalling payment of his benefit matches and his dissatisfaction at being dropped.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=194|ps=}} The club dropped to 14th spot in [[1913\u201314 Manchester United F.C. season|1913\u201314]], and only avoided relegation on the last day of the [[1914\u201315 Manchester United F.C. season|1914\u201315]] season after bribing Liverpool to lose 2\u20130 at Old Trafford; Meredith this time played no part in [[1915 British football betting scandal|the resulting bribery scandal]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=196|ps=}} He instead claimed to be baffled as to why his teammates refused to pass to him during the game.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=197|ps=}}\n\nDuring the First World War he actually played a match against United, making a guest appearance for [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]], with Vale recording a 5\u20132 victory at the [[Old Recreation Ground]].{{sfn|Kent|1996|ps=}} Frustrated with the club for delaying payments over his benefit match, he also played as a guest for Manchester City.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=204|ps=}} After the war ended he demanded a free transfer, and was repulsed that the club demanded a transfer fee, stating that the transfer market was a \"degrading business\" for players.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=205|ps=}} On 7 May 1921, at 46 years, 281 days, he became [[List of Manchester United F.C. records and statistics|United's oldest ever player]] when he took to the field in a league game against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]].\n\n===Return to Manchester City===\nIn 1921 he returned to Manchester City on a free transfer.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=208|ps=}} He played 25 first team games in the [[1921\u201322 Manchester City F.C. season|1921\u201322]] season, helping City to record a derby victory over rivals Manchester United.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=208|ps=}} He featured once in the [[1922\u201323 Manchester City F.C. season|1922\u201323]] campaign, playing the club's final game at [[Hyde Road Football Stadium|Hyde Road]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=208|ps=}} He played four [[FA Cup]] and two [[Football League First Division|First Division]] games in the [[1923\u201324 Manchester City F.C. season|1923\u201324]] season. Mangnall, now his manager at City, shocked [[Manchester]] when he selected Meredith for the cup game with [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] at the [[Goldstone Ground]], but was vindicated with a 5\u20131 victory; Meredith also scored a goal, though this was due to a poor mistake from the Brighton goalkeeper.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=215|ps=}} He played both games against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]] in the next round, a 0\u20130 draw at [[Maine Road]] and 1\u20130 win at [[Ninian Park]], and claimed an assist in the goal that settled the tie.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=216|ps=}} His last match was against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] in the semi-finals at the age of 49 years and 245 days, making him [[List of Manchester City F.C. records and statistics|City's oldest ever player]]; the game ended in a 2\u20131 defeat.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=218|ps=}}\n\n==International career==\nMeredith won his first cap for [[Wales national football team|Wales]] in a 2\u20132 draw with [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] on 16 March 1895 in [[Belfast]].<ref name=\"Chirk's Billy Meredith\">{{citation|title=Chapter Five \u2013 Chirk's Billy Meredith|url=http://www.chirkaaafc.com/chapter5.html|publisher=chirkaaafc.com|accessdate=10 February 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219151403/http://www.chirkaaafc.com/chapter5.html|archivedate=19 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He won 12 caps in the 1890s, but was forced to miss six games as his club would not let him play in games that clashed with league fixtures.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=56|ps=}} Wales could compete with Ireland, but were regularly beaten by [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] and [[England national football team|England]]. On 26 March 1900, Wales played for the first time in South Wales, at [[Cardiff Arms Park]], and Meredith scored a goal to earn the Welsh a celebrated 1\u20131 draw with England.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=57|ps=}} After serving his suspension, he returned to Wales for the [[British Home Championship]] title victory in [[1906\u201307 British Home Championship|1907]], the nation's first success in the competition. In those three games, he scored against Ireland in a 3\u20132 victory, and captained Wales to a 1\u20130 win over Scotland and a 1\u20131 draw with England.{{sfn|Harding|1998|pp=175\u201376|ps=}} Wales were denied a late penalty against the English, and Meredith was later recorded to have said \"never mind, little Wales will win some day [against England]. May I be there at the death.\"{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=179|ps=}}\n\nAfter draws with Ireland and Scotland, Meredith \"wept unashamedly\" as he helped Wales to beat England 2\u20131 at [[Arsenal Stadium|Highbury]] to claim the [[1919\u201320 British Home Championship|1920 British Home Championship]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=206|ps=}} It was only his second victory against the English in 20 attempts, and it marked the last of his 48 caps.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=207|ps=}} Though his record number of caps was later surpassed, at 45 years and 229 days he remains the [[Wales national football team records|oldest player]] to win a Wales cap. He was actually chosen by the selectors for 71 consecutive matches, but only made 48 appearances as his clubs regularly refused to release him for international duty.{{sfn|Brandon|1978|p=170|ps=}}\n\n==Style of play==\nMeredith was able to avoid injury throughout his career, despite the extremely physical nature of the game during the period.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=51|ps=}} This was due in part to his extraordinary balance and agility, which allowed him to avoid clumsy challenges, and the toughness he had built up from spending his adolescence working in the mines.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=52|ps=}} A model professional, he spent his spare time improving his game with extra training sessions and maintained peak physical fitness by avoiding alcohol and tobacco.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=53|ps=}} His \"gimmick\" was to chew on a [[toothpick]] during matches, and this unusual trait was picked up on by cartoonists of the time.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=54|ps=}}\n\nWriting a 1947 critique of [[Stanley Matthews]], Meredith criticised the lack of direct play on show in the 1940s and stated that when he was playing that \"I knew what was expected of me&nbsp;\u2013 to beat the wing-half and the full-back, take the ball down to the corner flag and centre\".{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=241|ps=}} His ball control skills were unparalleled, leaving opposition players unable to tackle him.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=242|ps=}} He also was an extremely accurate passer and crosser of the ball.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=244|ps=}} His dribbling and crossing gave him a large advantage over rival wingers, who relied solely on speed to beat opposition full-backs.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=244|ps=}} In addition to wing-play, he was also highly skilled at sending in long-range shots across the face of the goal, and could be relied upon to meet crosses from his left-winger with a powerful volley.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=246|ps=}}\n\nMeredith had to deal with extremely physical defences, and was often boxed into the corner of the pitch by as many as four players.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=246|ps=}} As his talents became widely regarded, more well organised defences would designate him with a man-marker, to try and isolate him from his teammates.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=247|ps=}} This often left him reliant on an unselfish inside-right partner willing to fetch and carry the ball for him without expecting much in terms of goals or glory in return.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=250|ps=}} A hard-working wing-half would also improve Meredith's effectiveness by winning the ball and sending him a pass down the flank.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=250|ps=}} The best teams he played in also had a centre-forward able to make the most of his accurate crosses.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=250|ps=}}\n\n==Players' Union==\n{{Quote box|quote=\"I have devoted myself to football and I have become a better player than most men because I have denied myself much that men prize&nbsp;... They congratulate me and give me caps but they will not give me a penny more than men are earning in the reserve team, some of them perhaps do not trouble themselves to improve themselves and don't worry about taking care of condition. If football is a man's livelihood and he does more than others for his employer, why is he not entitled to better pay than others? So far as I can make out, the sole reason why the best footballers in England are prevented from earning better than men of lesser ability and experience is purely sentimental.\"|source=\u2014 Meredith made a passionate and eloquent case for abandoning the maximum wage.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=126|ps=}}|width=35%|align=right}}\nMeredith organised the first meeting of the [[Players' Union]] (PU) in December 1907.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=129|ps=}} Meredith had previously been involved with the [[Association Footballers' Union]] (the \"AFU\"), the first attempt by football players in England to organise a [[trade union]]. The Players' Union, like the AFU before it, sought the relaxation of restrictions on transfers and wages.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/how-players-won-footballs-100-years-war-431441.html |newspaper=The Independent |title=How players won football's 100 years war |date=10 January 2007}}</ref> Others made the argument that a free market wage structure would ruin the amateur principles the sport was founded on, but Meredith felt that these words rang hollow considering that club directors and shareholders made vast profits.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=127|ps=}} At the first annual meeting in December 1908, the PU stated their aims as to allow unlimited wages, the right to transfer from club to club, and for players to take a percentage of any transfer fee.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=130|ps=}}\n\nWith the union threatening strike action, particularly at international matches, in April 1909 [[the Football Association]] insisted that all players agree to leave the union and pledge loyalty to the FA.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=133|ps=}} Manchester United refused to issue the revised contracts to its players, and FA suspended the entire squad.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=135}} The club then refused to pay the players in lieu of their suspension, and so the players instead took away ornaments from the club's office before Mangnall persuaded them to return the items.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=135}} The players continued to train, and captain [[Charlie Roberts]] came up with the name of Outcasts F.C.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=137|ps=}} The FA organised a meeting of 200 players, excluding the Outcasts, but a rambling speech from chairman [[Charles Clegg (footballer)|Charles Clegg]] failed to win them over, and an agreement was reached where the PU would be recognised by the FA.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=140|ps=}}\n\nIn October 1909, the Union balloted its members over the organisation's membership of the [[General Federation of Trade Unions (United Kingdom)|General Federation of Trade Unions]] (GTFU).{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=140|ps=}} The result of the vote, a decisive \"no\" to GFTU support, effectively supported the FA's position that professional footballers were fundamentally different from workmen in other industries.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=140|ps=}} Meredith resumed league football in November 1909, bemoaning his view that \"many players refuse to take things seriously and continue to live a kind of schoolboy life\".{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=143|ps=}}\n\n==Personal life and legacy==\nHe married Ellen Negus in 1901, and the couple had two daughters.{{sfn|Harding|1998|pp=48\u20139|ps=}} He was a supporter of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]].{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=125|ps=}} He ran businesses throughout his career, with little success, and was declared bankrupt in July 1909 after his outfitting shop was damaged by fire.{{sfn|harvnb|Harding|1998|p=135}} During the 1910s he ran a [[public house]] (despite being a teetotaller) and later pursued an interest in the film industry by buying shares in numerous [[Stretford]] [[Movie theater|cinemas]] in the 1930s.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=209|ps=}} He also starred in 1926 picture ''[[The Ball of Fortune]]'', playing himself as a football trainer; the film received generally positive reviews.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=225|ps=}} In 1928, together with former colleague [[Charlie Roberts]] he became a coach for the ambitious but short-lived [[Manchester Central F.C.|Manchester Central]]. Meredith's son-in-law, former City captain [[Charlie Pringle]], was a player.{{sfn|James|2008|pp=147\u2013166|ps=}} He retained a passion for football, and spent much of his retirement discussing the game with former colleagues and regulars at his hotel, the Stretford Road Hotel, which he ran from 1930 to 1945.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=230|ps=}} He rarely missed the chance to attend a Wales game in the 1920s and 1930s.{{sfn|Harding|1998|p=230|ps=}}\n\n[[File:Meredith shirt.jpg|thumb|200px|A Wales national team football shirt which was worn by Billy Meredith in the early 1900s, with Welsh cap. On display at the [[National Football Museum]] in [[Manchester]].]]\nMeredith died in [[Withington]], Manchester in April 1958 at the age of 83, two months after the [[Munich air disaster]], which claimed the lives of eight [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] players.<ref>{{citation |title=Billy Meredith |url=http://www.redcafe.net/wiki/Billy_Meredith |publisher=redcafe.net |accessdate=14 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130501012403/http://www.redcafe.net/wiki/Billy_Meredith |archivedate=1 May 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> After he spent many years in an unmarked grave, the [[Professional Footballers' Association]], the [[Football Association of Wales|Welsh FA]], Manchester City and Manchester United all agreed to cover the cost of upkeep on a new headstone.<ref>{{citation |title=Profile|url=http://www.stretford-end.com/2011/02/legends-billy-meredith-player-profile/ |publisher=stretford-end.com |accessdate=14 February 2013}}</ref> Meredith is honoured in the [[hall of fame]] at the [[City of Manchester Stadium]].<ref>{{citation  |title=Winifred weeps as dad joins legends |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/sport/football/manchester_city/s/79/79173_winifred_weeps_as_dad_joins_legends_.html |newspaper=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date=25 January 2004 |accessdate=26 August 2011}}</ref> It was announced in August 2007 that Meredith was one of the 10 new inductees for 2007 to the [[English Football Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.nationalfootballmuseum.com/pages/fame/Inductees/billymeredith.htm |title=Football Hall of Fame&nbsp;\u2013 Billy Meredith |accessdate=25 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080520204806/http://www.nationalfootballmuseum.com/pages/fame/Inductees/billymeredith.htm |archivedate=20 May 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Division\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[